===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|boy|boy|lang=enm}}, {{term|boye||servant, commoner, knave, boy|lang=enm}}, from [[Old English]] *{{term||bōia|boy|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|title=Anglo-Frisian|bō-jan-|younger brother|lang=en}}, diminutive of {{proto|Germanic|title=Proto-Germanic base|bō-|brother, close male relation|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|bhā-||bhāt-|father, elder brother, brother|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|boai||boy|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|frs|-}} {{term|boi||boy, young gentleman|lang=frs}}, and perhaps to [[Old English]] proper name ''Bōia''. Also related to [[Flemish]] {{term|boe||brother|lang=vls}}, Norwegian dialectal {{term|boa||brother|lang=no}}, Dutch {{term|boef||rogue, knave|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} dialectal {{term|Bube||boy, lad, knave|lang=de}}. See also {{l|en|bully}}.

